2 HOUSE BILL 1071
1 (2013 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
2 BY adding to
3 Article – Environment
4 Section 4–203(b)(5) 4–203(b)(2)(xi)
5 Annotated Code of Maryland
6 (2013 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
7 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
8 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
9 Article – Environment
10 4–203.
11 (b) (1) The Department shall adopt rules and regulations which establish
12 criteria and procedures for stormwater management in Maryland.
13 (2) The rules and regulations shall:
14 (v) 1. Specify the minimum content of the local ordinances or the
15 rules and regulations of the affected county governing body to be adopted which may be
16 done by inclusion of a model ordinance or model rules and regulations; [and]
17 2. Establish regulations and a model ordinance that require:
18 A. The implementation of environmental site design to the
19 maximum extent practicable;
20 B. The review and modification, if necessary, of planning and
21 zoning or public works ordinances to remove impediments to environmental site design
22 implementation; and
23 C. A developer to demonstrate that environmental site
24 design has been implemented to the maximum extent practicable and standard best
25 management practices have been used only where absolutely necessary; AND
26 3. ESTABLISH PROVISIONS AND A MODEL ORDINANCE
27 THAT REQUIRE LOCAL STORMWATER MANAGEMENT PROGRAMS TO ENFORCE
28 STORMWATER MANAGEMENT REGULATIONS ON AGRICULTURAL LAND WITH THE
29 ADVICE AND CONSENT OF THE LOCAL SOIL CONSERVATION DISTRICT;
30 (5) IN THE MARYLAND STORMWATER DESIGN MANUAL,
31 INCORPORATED BY REFERENCE IN COMAR 26.17.02, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL:

HOUSE BILL 1071 3
1 (I) DEFINE AGRICULTURE AND ACCESSORY USES ON
2 AGRICULTURAL LAND, INCLUDING ON–FARM PROCESSING AND OFFICE SPACE, AS
3 DISTINCT FROM COMMERCIAL DEVELOPMENT; AND
4 (II) ALLOW FOR FLEXIBILITY IN ENFORCEMENT OF THE
5 STORMWATER MANAGEMENT REGULATIONS ON AGRICULTURAL LAND.
6 (ix) 1. Establish a comprehensive process for approving grading
7 and sediment control plans and stormwater management plans; and
8 2. Specify that the comprehensive process established under
9 item (i) of this item takes into account the cumulative impacts of both plans; [and]
10 (x) Incorporate the most recent precipitation data available; AND
11 (XI) 1. IN CONSULTATION WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF
12 AGRICULTURE, DEFINE “AGRITOURISM”; AND
13 2. CONSIDER BEST MANAGEMENT PRACTICES FOR
14 STORMWATER MANAGEMENT FOR AGRITOURISM, INCLUDING:
15 A. THE CREATION OF A STANDARD PLAN FOR
16 TEMPORARY PARKING AREAS; AND
17 B. THE USE OF PASTURE, MEADOWS, AND CROPLAND
18 FOR THE TREATMENT OF STORMWATER RUNOFF.
19 4–204.
20 (c) Each county or municipality may provide by ordinance for the review and
21 approval of stormwater management plans by the local soil conservation district.
22 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That Montgomery County and the
23 Montgomery Soil Conservation District jointly shall:
24 (1) in consultation with the Department of the Environment, review the
25 county’s current process for reviewing and approving stormwater management plans for
26 agritourism;
27 (2) as part of the review required under item (1) of this section:
28 (i) examine how other counties in the State review and approve
29 stormwater management plans for agritourism;

4 HOUSE BILL 1071
1 (ii) identify challenges and approaches to improve the agritourism
2 stormwater management plan review and coordination between the county and the soil
3 conservation district; and
4 (iii) recommend changes to the review and approval process for
5 stormwater management plans for agritourism in the county; and
6 (3) on or before December 31, 2026, report the findings under this section
7 to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the
8 General Assembly.
9 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
10 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
